  "output": "## Performance Analysis — jobsquare\n\nQuick note on scope: this is a Python batch pipeline (fetch → filter → dedupe → notify), not a React app, so I've mapped your five categories onto their nearest real equivalents here: SQLite N+1s instead of query-layer N+1s, hot-loop recomputation instead of re-renders, HTTP/regex caching instead of memoization, and working-set bloat instead of classic leaks (this is a short-lived CLI process, so nothing survives across runs to \"leak\").\n\n### 1. N+1 query pattern — `Store.diff()` (store.py:55-74)\n\nFor every job in the batch, you run a separate `SELECT`, then a separate `INSERT`/`UPDATE`. With Microsoft/Amazon/Google boards alone capped at hundreds–thousands of postings per run, that's 2×N round trips through the sqlite3 C API on every single run, even when almost nothing changed.\n\n```python\n# now: one SELECT + one INSERT/UPDATE per job, in a Python loop\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    ...\n```\n\nBatch it — one `IN (...)` lookup (chunked under SQLite's ~999 param limit) plus `executemany` for the writes:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n\n    existing: dict[str, str] = {}\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 900):\n        chunk = keys[i:i + 900]\n        q = f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({','.join('?' * len(chunk))})\"\n        existing.update({r[\"key\"]: r[\"content_hash\"] for r in cur.execute(q, chunk)})\n\n    new, changed, touched, inserts, updates = [], [], [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        prior = existing.get(job.key)\n        r = {**job.to_row(), \"now\": now}\n        if prior is None:\n            new.append(job); inserts.append(r)\n        elif prior != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job); updates.append(r)\n        else:\n            touched.append((now, job.key))\n\n    if inserts:\n        cur.executemany(\"\"\"INSERT INTO jobs (...) VALUES (:key,:source,...,:now,:now)\"\"\", inserts)\n    if updates:\n        cur.executemany(\"\"\"UPDATE jobs SET title=:title,... WHERE key=:key\"\"\", updates)\n    if touched:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", touched)\n\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nThis turns O(N) round trips into O(N/900 + 3) statements.\n\n### 2. Redundant computation — regex recompiled per job (filters.py:11-26)\n\n`match()` calls `_compile(exclude)` and `_compile(include)` fresh **on every job**, and `filter_jobs` calls `match()` once per job — so for a 2,000-job batch with 10 keywords, you're compiling the same 10 regexes 2,000 times.\n\n```python\n# filters.py — now\ndef filter_jobs(jobs, rules):\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=rules.get(\"include_keywords\"), ...)]  # match() recompiles every call\n```\n\nHoist compilation out of the loop:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = None\n    if max_age := rules.get(\"max_age_days\"):\n        cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=float(max_age))\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    locations = [l.lower() for l in rules.get(\"locations\") or []]\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude,\n                                      locations=locations, cutoff=cutoff)]\n```\n\n(`match()` then just uses the pre-compiled lists directly instead of calling `_compile` again.)\n\n### 3. Redundant computation — `content_hash` recomputed twice per changed job (models.py:66-69, store.py:67-96)\n\n`content_hash` is a plain `@property` (no caching), doing a SHA-256 hash every access. In `diff()`, a changed job hits it once for the comparison (`row[\"content_hash\"] != job.content_hash`) and again inside `_update` → `to_row()`. Same story for `key` (computed in the SELECT, then again inside `to_row()`).\n\nSince `Job` uses `slots=True`, `functools.cached_property` needs an explicit slot:\n\n```python\n@dataclass(slots=True)\nclass Job:\n    ...\n    _content_hash: str | None = field(default=None, repr=False, compare=False)\n\n    @property\n    def content_hash(self) -> str:\n        if self._content_hash is None:\n            blob = \"|\".join((self.title, self.location, self.url, self.department))\n            self._content_hash = hashlib.sha256(blob.encode()).hexdigest()[:16]\n        return self._content_hash\n```\n\nMinor in isolation, but combined with the batched `diff()` above (which computes `to_row()` once per job up front and reuses it for both the comparison and the write), this becomes free — worth doing both together rather than separately.\n\n### 4. Caching opportunity — HTTP conditional requests for the \"simple\" ATS fetchers\n\nThe `_simple`-based fetchers (greenhouse, lever, ashby, smartrecruiters, recruitee, workable — fetchers.py:641-648) re-download the entire board every run even if nothing changed. Greenhouse/Ashby/SmartRecruiters all support `ETag`/`Last-Modified`. Persisting the ETag per source in the `meta` table (you already have `get_meta`/`set_meta` for exactly this) and sending `If-None-Match` would let a 304 skip the parse+diff entirely for unchanged boards:\n\n```python\nasync def _fetch(client, source):\n    company = source[\"company\"]\n    method, url = url_builder(company)\n    meta_key = f\"etag:{ats_name}:{company}\"\n    etag = store.get_meta(meta_key)  # needs Store threaded through, or a light cache dict\n    headers = {\"If-None-Match\": etag} if etag else {}\n    r = await _request(client, url, method=method, headers=headers)\n    if r.status_code == 304:\n        return []  # unchanged since last run\n    if new_etag := r.headers.get(\"ETag\"):\n        store.set_meta(meta_key, new_etag)\n    return parser(company, r.json())\n```\n\nGiven 125 sources in `sources.yaml`, this cuts real bandwidth/latency on every scheduled run (you're running this every 12h per the recent Twilio-notification commit), not just CPU.\n\n### 5. \"Memory leak\"-adjacent finding — `Job.raw` is parsed and retained but never read\n\nEvery source-fetcher packs the full raw API payload into `Job.raw` (fetchers.py, e.g. lines 72, 92, 121…). I grepped the whole codebase — `raw` is never read anywhere downstream; `to_row()` (models.py:73) explicitly `pop`s it before the DB write, and that's its only consumer. So for the lifetime of every run, you're holding a full raw JSON dict per job — for the big boards (Microsoft/Amazon/Google, capped at 30-40 pages × 10-20/page) that's hundreds to low-thousands of otherwise-unused dict objects live in memory simultaneously, worst case in `dry_run` mode (pipeline.py:36-40) where they're printed and discarded with zero use of `raw`.\n\nSince it's genuinely dead weight, the simplest fix is dropping it, not gating it:\n\n```python\n@dataclass(slots=True)\nclass Job:\n    ...\n    # raw: dict[str, Any] = field(default_factory=dict, repr=False)   # remove — never read\n```\n\nand delete the `raw={...}` kwargs at each call site, plus the `d.pop(\"raw\", None)` in `to_row()`. If you want it for future debugging, keep it but only under an opt-in env var / debug flag rather than unconditionally on every `Job`.\n\n---\n\n**No other leak-shaped issues found** — connections (`Store`, `httpx.AsyncClient`, `smtplib.SMTP`) are all properly scoped with `with`/`try-finally`, and pagination loops (Apple/Google/Two Sigma/Optiver/ByteDance) are correctly bounded by `max_pages`.\n\n**Priority order if you want to act on these**: #1 (batch `diff()`) is the highest-value fix since it runs on every job on every scheduled run; #2 and #5 are cheap wins; #4 (conditional GET) is the best bandwidth/latency win but requires threading `Store` into `fetch_all`, so it's the biggest lift.\n",
